Here's the extracted information from the images, maintaining absolute precision and without making any deductions:

**Title:** 2nd & 3rd floor equivalency

**Rule/Regulation:**
Areas higher than 17' and 26' above the first floor (that do not already count as floor area e.g., open atrium spaces and inaccessible attic spaces), count toward the gross floor area in the form of 2nd and 3rd floor equivalency regardless of the floor plan or usage of the space. Stairwells will be measured the same way that vaulted ceiling spaces are measured.

**Examples (from Fig 12):**
In the examples of Fig 12 below the highlighted areas count as follows:

*   **Area A**
    *   once as 1st floor,
    *   again as 2nd floor, and
    *   a third time as 3rd-floor equivalency

*   **Area B**
    *   once as 1st floor,
    *   again as 2nd-floor equivalency

**Note:**
200 sf of 3rd floor equivalency may be exempted where roof pitch is 4:12 or steeper (see "Height" section).

**Figure Caption:**
Fig 12 2nd & 3rd floor equivalency

**Labels and Measurements from Diagrams:**

*   **Diagram 1 (Left):**
    *   "Width of area that counts as 3rd-floor equivalency" (indicated by a double-headed arrow)
    *   "Width of area that counts as 2nd-floor equivalency" (indicated by a double-headed arrow)

    *   "Top of roof material (Typical)" (pointing to the top of the roof)
    *   "26'" (indicating a height from an unmarked reference line to the top of the roof material)
    *   "17'" (indicating a height from an unmarked reference line to a lower point on the roof structure)
    *   "A" (label for a hatched vertical section)

*   **Diagram 2 (Right):**
    *   "Width of area that counts as 3rd-floor equivalency" (indicated by a double-headed arrow)
    *   "Width of area that counts as 2nd-floor equivalency" (indicated by a double-headed arrow)
    *   "Inaccessible attic (or vaulted ceiling)" (pointing to the hatched area above the second floor)
